SIMPLE: equivocation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Equivocation
<hw>E*quiv`o*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The use of
expressions susceptible of a double signification, with a purpose to
mislead.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There being no room for <qex>equivocations</qex>, there is no need
of distinctions.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Prevarication; ambiguity; shuffling; evasion;
quibbling. See <er>Equivocal</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
<er>Prevaricate</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos></syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equivocator</ent>⟦br⟧
